{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17594396","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17594396"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T10:47:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T10:47:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15307"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15307","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15307"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.33,0,0.03,0.43]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7998"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65936"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7998","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7998"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15307"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51382"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8760"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19443"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19445"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22034"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65936","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65936"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA patient who has had several episodes of acute cholecystitis undergoes a cholecystectomy. When the gallbladder specimen is reviewed by the pathologist their report mentions outpouchings of mucosal epithelium extending through the gallbladder wall.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes these mucosal outpouchings?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Adenomyomatous hyperplasia","Budd-Chiari diverticula","Cholesterol deposits","Cholesterolosis","Rokitansky-Aschoff sinuses"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe described outpouchings are \u003Cstrong\u003ERokitansky-Aschoff sinuses\u003C/strong\u003E, which are characteristic microscopic findings in chronic cholecystitis. These are herniated mucosal invaginations that extend through the gallbladder wall muscle layer. These acquired lesions will be present in some 90% of resected gallbladders.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBudd-Chiari diverticula\u003C/strong\u003E is not a recognised gallbladder pathology. \u003Cstrong\u003ECholesterol deposits\u003C/strong\u003E appear as yellow streaks in the mucosa rather than outpouchings. \u003Cstrong\u003EAdenomyomatous hyperplasia\u003C/strong\u003E refers to thickening of the muscle wall itself. \u003Cstrong\u003ECholesterolosis\u003C/strong\u003E presents as yellow speckled mucosa (strawberry gallbladder) due to lipid-laden macrophages.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Rokitansky-Aschoff sinuses are epithelial invaginations through the gallbladder wall that develop in chronic cholecystitis","Chronic cholecystitis is commonly associated with gallstones and leads to structural changes in the gallbladder wall"],"references":["Dave HD, Shumway KR, Al Obaidi NM. Physiology, Biliary. [Updated 2022 Dec 15]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537107/","Nightingale, J. M. (2012). Applied anatomy and physiology of the gastrointestinal tract (GIT). Gastrointestinal Tract Imaging E-Book: Gastrointestinal Tract Imaging E-Book, 45","Podolsky, D. K., Camilleri, M., Fitz, J. G., Kalloo, A. N., Shanahan, F., \u0026 Wang, T. C. (Eds.). (2015). Yamada\u0027s textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Lammert F, Gurusamy K, Ko CW, Miquel JF, M\u00e9ndez-S\u00e1nchez N, Portincasa P, van Erpecum KJ, van Laarhoven CJ, Wang DQ. Gallstones. Nat Rev Dis Primers. 2016 Apr 28;2:16024. doi: 10.1038/nrdp.2016.24. PMID: 27121416"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51382"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15307"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51382","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51382"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-27T20:53:48+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-27T20:54:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7998"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65936"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4928","links":{"self":"https